<p>Welcome back, Vis. I was wondering where you were. I figured you were (A) out tending your olive or (B)taking a rest after that knock-down dragout fight with Maestro. :) So the Internet is being interrupted again. Suprise, surprise!<BR/><BR/>(Ah, dear Maestro; mistress of the oblique. I must admit I found her pretty amusing. Her shtick was, "Psst! Psst! I know something you don't!" She never would give a straight answer to anything. Once she jumped on you, however, I stopped laughing.)<BR/><BR/>Since last time I attempted to e-mail President-elect Obama. Change.gov would not take my email; neither would his website. I did manage finally to get through to Obama's campaign website (because I was a contributor) but all I got back was a generic response. I put a letter in the mail last week. Here is the text:<BR/><BR/>Dear President-elect Obama:<BR/><BR/>Ccongratulations to you and Vice-President-elect Biden. I wish all the best to you and your families. <BR/><BR/>            I see from your website Change.gov that you are seeking the input of everyday Americans. Well, I am very happy to do my part. <BR/><BR/>Problem 1: The Economy <BR/><BR/>To paraphrase the Emerald City guard in &#8220;The Wizard of Oz:&#8221; No More Bailouts. For Nobody. No How.&#8221; <BR/><BR/>   Not unless those asking for them agree (in writing, with witnesses) to: <BR/><BR/>A)    Keep as much of their workforce working as possible; <BR/><BR/>B)    Forgo executive bonuses; <BR/><BR/>C)    Cut dividends (with people losing their jobs and houses and sleeping in tents, the bottom line has been moved); <BR/><BR/>D)    Operate with complete transparency; in other words, they cannot take our tax money, stick it in their pockets (or someone else&#8217;s) and then refuse to tell what they did with it. <BR/><BR/>Next: Repeal Bush&#8217;s tax cuts, reinstate the estate tax, give tax breaks to family farmers, small businesses, and to the middle class (those earning between $50-$100 thousand<BR/>per year. <BR/><BR/>Then: Restore the Depression-Era laws that were originally created to prevent things like this from ever happening again---laws that Phil Gramm and his ilk have so gleefully and systematically dismantled. <BR/><BR/>Problem 2:  Unemployment <BR/><BR/>You have expressed your interest in creating green jobs. There is certainly plenty of work to be done here in America, particularly on our infrastructure: roads, bridges, sewers, levees and schools. We also need to preserve and protect our natural resources (wetlands, parks, rivers, lakes, etc.). Another area that needs serious revamping is transportation: mass transit and railroads. <BR/><BR/>Problem 3: Housing <BR/><BR/>Every effort needs to be made to keep people from losing their homes, whether it be by renegotiating/restructuring mortgages, or granting tax incentives to lenders who are willing to be flexible. <BR/><BR/>      Part of your employment program could include rehabilitating foreclosed homes and building new ones to provide energy-efficient and affordable housing for everyone. (Brad Pitt has being doing an excellent job of this in New Orleans. Are you familiar with &#8220;Katrina houses?&#8221; If not, Google them.) <BR/><BR/>      Well, that&#8217;s all for now. I&#8217;ll leave you with a joke: A few weeks before the election, I saw a newspaper cartoon. One guy says (I&#8217;m paraphrasing here): &#8220;I&#8217;d rather vote for a candidate I can sit down and have a beer with.&#8221; The second guy says, &#8220;Yeah, but will he be around for the hangover?&#8221; <BR/><BR/> Thanks for listening, Pres.-elect. Merry Christmas and Happy Kwanzaa to you and yours. May you have a blessed and peaceful New Year. <BR/><BR/>Sincerely, <BR/><BR/><BR/><BR/>Gloria A. <BR/><BR/>I also sent an article from Ode magazine about communiity financing, another from GuardianUK about Bush's midnight bills, and a list of references:<BR/>  <BR/><BR/> Some recommended reading: <BR/>  <BR/><BR/>Thieves In High Places by Jim Hightower <BR/><BR/>The Great Unraveling by Paul Krugman <BR/><BR/>&#8220;25 Ways To Lift The Curse,&#8221; Mother Jones Vol. 33 #5 September/October 2008 <BR/><BR/>&#8220;Motor City Meltdown,&#8221; The Nation Vol. 287 #20 December 15, 2008 <BR/><BR/> <BR/>Useful websites: <BR/>  <BR/><BR/>AppolloAlliance.org <BR/><BR/>www.thevenusproject.com <BR/><BR/>www.cbpp.org (The Center on Budget and Policy Priorities) <BR/><BR/>I've started composing the next one; there will be four in all. While it's true they may choose to ignore me, I'm still going to throw my ideas out there and hope they take root.<BR/><BR/>Anyhoo, Happy Solstice, Merry Christmas, Happy Festivus, or whatever else you may observe.<BR/>Peace.<BR/><BR/>12/22/08</p>
