<dd class='comment-body'>
<p>"Bholanath" here.  Hope you don't mind me contacting/connecting here.<BR/><BR/>   Thank you for your kind words. Your understanding, both of yourself, your own nature, and of mine and others' natures passing through these sometimes suffocating times makes me weep also. The important thing, I think, is that we recognize one another (our Selves) in a big widespread community all over this world. We have been here in similar situations many times before, but seems like we have to experience intense isolation this time around. But it's a false illusory distance. And I am confident we will surely have those opportunities to realize communion around the dhuni fire one day, even in this cycle.<BR/> <BR/>   Sometimes I'm almost at the pit of despair at the tragedy of so few "out there/here" who are articulating both the horror and the humor of the situation, but I am full of gratitude for your presence (and most of the commentators) in cyber-world. Thanks and praises, Ras. Cyber-world is sure savin our asses, or our sanity at least.<BR/><BR/>   The one saving Grace that keeps me on the planet is MUSIC. In this round I've had the extraordinary Grace of studying with, hearing and accompanying-on-tour  the greatest living master musicians, dancers,  and nad-yogis on earth, many who've now passed on.  I wasn't born into it, didn't start till I was 21, but they all were incredibly kind and infinitely generous to this lame-ass white cracker who began the journey with only the desire to understand/comprehend/appreciate what they were doing, nothing more. It was in Vietnam days, and I just wanted to be around something "real" and learn something, before the world blew up. So in '68 I hitched across Canada (draft-dodger), caught a $100 plane ride from Newfoundland to Scotland, hitched my way to Benares. Ravi Shankar and Allah Rakha had given me a note of intro to the Mahant of Sankat Mochan Hanuman temple, who was my first teacher. Along the way I've studied with 10 monster muthafuckers, both Hindu and Muslim. It's a never-ending journey, of course, and I continue my studies (my ass-being-kicked) with two top bad-asses from Orissa. And I'm naturally an unabashed Hanuman-bhakt and Kali-bhakt. Needless to say it's always been a hard landing and integration coming back from many 1-2 year sojourns over India-side. The stunning beauty of all I've witnessed stays always present and tears run every day, as I listen to recordings of the dudes and chicks who've dropped my head to the floor repeatedly.<BR/><BR/>   I'm in New Mexico now, 1/2 hour north of Taos, where I've been based for 20 years. Just this year found my lady love/truth-consort (at 61!). I was in India for 9 months in 2007. I played every night for a month in the temple in Gangotri. Love the Himalayas, Himachal, Gharwal, can't take the plains/cities much any more. Didn't yet make it to Arunachala, but have friends there. Have tried to play in Amerikan temples (Shiva, Hanuman, Kali, etc.) over the years, and also with some of the leading pop-kirtan wallahs, but it all mostly drained my energy/spirit. Too too much of that glam glam and about-me shit that you know of so well. But sometimes the good posse comes together, and we rock the house with praises to the one-tooth trunk-face, and all the others (aspects of us and life).<BR/>   Being in the southwest, I did spend time (9 months) on Hopi. I try to visit when I can for dances. Cleanest place on the earth IMHO. This summer we witnessed a torrential storm develop as the Flute Dancers ascended to the top of Second Mesa. Also in '82 I saw the last Snake Dance that was open to outsiders. Same thing happened, plus the most beautiful songs ever heard, and that evidence of collective unified concentration resulting in Grace from the Devic realms. When, in '82,  I first made it there, I got the feeling fully downloaded about my spirit being actually really at home on this continent for the first time in my life. That's why, though I bailed in Vietnam days, I'm reluctant to bail again. I watch my back, my friends' backs, and keep up the relative invisibility, but say 'yes' to any opportunity to play out. Its a moment to moment balance deciding how to move and where, out there, on planes, on the highways...not giving into fear, reading the 'signs', moving with that "ease" you speak of. We are all under the Protection, right?<BR/><BR/>   A strange thing happened after the 9 months on Hopi. Was fresh off the rez (and Big Mountain camp) in Flagstaff. United Nuclear Corporation was giving a slide-show/PR/bullshit presentation in the Hyatt to convince everyone how cool their plan for uranium-mining next to Grand Canyon would be. Hall was full, some Natives standing around the back. I "coincidently" met up with the CEO in the men's room. Holy shit! He spoke first - " Isn't it great we can dialogue, blah blah..." Something happened and I must have channelled a combination of Hanuman's flawless oratory and the "way-it-is" of the Hopi elders, 'cause I flamed him with the truth of the situation. Anyway.....next day, I read in the newspaper: the dude is dead of a heart-attack! The mining project never materialized. I can not in any way say what it means. It just simply occurred, is a strange memory, and raises all sorts of questions.<BR/><BR/>   At the time of my first Saturn return, '74 in Delhi, I thought I wanted to "get out of here" for good. I climbed to the top of abandoned minaret, took strong medicine, stood on the ledge, turned my eyes to the sky, asked for .....well, something. I had been meditating on Sri Yantra for months. She, Kali-ma, came with full force. Showed the full grand play of her lila, all the Devi Bhagavatam stories before my eyes. Proceeded, in the form of every predator that ever existed, to devour me (in the form of every prey) for eons across light-years. That took some time. The next thing was the consuming morphed into fucking. We fucked in every form imaginable, for ages. She showed me her ultimate nature is love and compassion incomparable. Showed me the Earth is the true Island of Jewels (Manidvipa). Witnessed each of my breath-cycles enveloped in Her bringing about the creation and destruction of the universes. I was the corpse of Mahadev, she the life-giver. Anyway, that was once upon a time. You and I, we've seen a lot, lots has happened. The Kali revelation (the sexy parts) is something that I can't share with the new age Ramakrishna devotee Kali worshippers in California, unfortunately (or the Ammachi devotees). They love my playing, but want me to just shut up otherwise. Oh well. Many don't like my long history with the cactus allies who've helped my practice from the beginning either. Or the green herbal irie-ness. Jeezuz, get over yourselves, people!<BR/><BR/>Much of my later life has concerned animal friends too. Being a Hanuman-bhakt, the monkey research was over the top for me. Led me on a research journey that became eventually a "friendly" relationship with the ALF and ELF. Not active now, except as a lone nut. Worked in wildlife rehab and ran the local animal shelter here for 3 years.<BR/><BR/>Just wanted to touch bases with you, let you know a bit of my history/perspective here from 7500 ft. in the falling snow on the second day of the new year as the sun conjuncts pluto (shiva). May shiva's third-eye laser atomize all the dip-shit psycho alien monotheistic gold-worshipping freaks who are so retarded they can only miss all the awesome magic and try to shit on the beauty, as their way of spending their unacknowledged/unappreciated precious birth here.<BR/>And, can you please make this happen, if not by Xmas, then at least by spring?!<BR/><BR/>You're welcome here any time. Otherwise we meet in Italy, Germany, or India. (I have musician co-conspirators in Umbria and Berlin too.) We got the good mezcal also on hand, or if not, the patron silver or equal.<BR/><BR/>As 'anonymous' said today:<BR/>"we are closer than brothers who dare the demons and transcend the mortal fears"</p>
</dd>
