<dd class='comment-body'>
<p>Jj, your post reminds me for some reason of this egregore thought that I've had for a while.  Don't think I've ever written or talked about it with anyone. Egregore is a word that I don't know the origin of, but what it means is a collection of dead people's souls... or probably not exactly souls. Don't know if they are souls or not, dead people's personalities?  They gather in clots on the infra-red plane of existence, the next one up from this dense matter plane.  See Robert Monroe's writings for instances. Kyle Griffith's <I>War in Heaven</I> is another good source.<BR/><BR/>The idea as I get it is that some self-centered entity collects a bunch of followers in this material lifetime, sucking their energy to feed his own, and when he dies he continues to suck the energy from his living followers.  At the same time, those followers that worship him are drawn to him after death, and become a part of a group mind on the infra-red plane, a group mind that feeds off of the religious (or other) practices of those still alive.  One corollary to this would be that the religion this entity founded would always be looking for converts, and would encourage all followers to have as many children as possible, these children to be raised in the faith.<BR/><BR/>I'm not picking on Catholics or Mormons here, though they are visible examples. The Baal worshipers of the old Middle East are too, as are the Aztecs.  The Aztecs were into human sacrifice big-time; Bernal Diaz who accompanied and journaled Cortez' conquest of Mexico reported 15,000 freshly flayed skulls displayed on wooden racks when the Spaniards entered Tenochtitlan.  The crowd of worshipers were hypnotized and their energy sucked up by the egregore, along with the life energy of the sacrifices.  Diaz writes that the priests smeared the sacrificial blood into their long uncut hair, stiffening it with stinking gore that was never washed out. (The details make it real, don't you think?) It was all feeding the egregore. <BR/><BR/>The Aztecs related well to the bloody, tortured, crucified god that the Spaniards brought, but their pet egregores were no longer fed; the sacrifice now went to a different grouping of energies.  Some say the egregores of the Aztecs migrated North in search of food and became the Windigo of the northern tribes before eventually fading away.<BR/><BR/>What I'm getting at here is the egregore of the Jews.  For some time, perhaps centuries but at least for a century, we have been hearing about the six million dead Jewish victims.  The Zionists tried it out after WWI, claiming six million dead Jews, but it didn't fly.  Ran it up the flagpole without getting any salutes after WWII as well, but they have managed to draw attention to the thought-form since the 1970s when they invented the holocaust scenario.  Always six million Jews dying.  <BR/><BR/>Mediocre research will show that the Jewish population of Europe didn't diminish very much based on the censuses before and after either WWI or WWII; not by six million anyway.  What I'm thinking about here is that maybe the egregore is working on the idea that six million newly dead recruits would produce some sort of critical mass, and that critical mass would be enough to turn the whole planet into its worshipers and food source.<BR/><BR/>So how many Jews are concentrated in Israel right now?  And why is some perverse part of them just begging to get whacked really hard?</p>
</dd>
