   <BR/><BR/>while &#39;slave labor&#39; at the time was more of an economic concern for the south getting product to market; (the initial outlay per &quot;head&quot; was 3-5K for a field-hand, the north had no such initial outlay of investment, as workers were not purchased outright, nor housed, nor clothed, but singularly paid a pittance in wages)   getting product &#39;through&#39; the market was the prime economic concern.    had the federal gov backed off the tariff rate, its doubtful that the south would have taken their legal right to secession frm the voluntary union, as they&#39;d put up w/lower tariffs for over 40yrs.  <BR/><BR/>if you read thru dilorenzo&#39;s archive, you&#39;ll find that a few northern states, NY for one i believe, threw hissy fits and threatened secession on numerous occasions when &#39;it&#39; felt that it was suffering neglect for their interests...never had the balls to follow thru though.<BR/><BR/>&#39;I agree with Hamilton on the need for protectionism and I do not agree with secession. The civil war gave the Hamiltonians the authority to do everything<BR/>they wanted, and thats why we have had one war after another and one financial crisis after another for 150 years.&#39;<BR/><BR/>the hamiltonian centrists/lincoln already claimed that authority and upheld their claim to it by; invasion of the south to collect that tariff money, suspension of the constitution &amp; habeas corpus, shuttering the free press in the north, mandatory conscription of immigrants (see dilorenzo&#39;s &quot;Gangs of NY&quot;)  imprisonment of dissenters(north), and open outright fuking warfare on southern civilians......a little evil to do good, eh?  ends justify the means?   surrrrrre.<BR/><BR/>even if no effort to stop them bulldozing of states rights had been made, the outcome would have been much less bloody, but the same.   at least some tried to stop them.   as far as the mindset of j.q. southerner, they were fighting an invading force in their home