n&#39;t include women (or their rights to education, and vox as participating members of society ) on any enlightened note.<BR/><BR/>M&amp;D is a seminal, comparative work for its day... world religions, philosophies, governments, sciences, and arts, exco/esoteric -   drawing from all of recorded time to Pike&#39;s present (1870&#39;s).   <BR/><BR/><BR/>and on the issue of the klan. i&#39;m sure there were operatives of klan that were active w/in scot rite, north &amp; south.  Pike had reached the pinnacle of networking w/in the southern jurisdiction of the scot rite. <BR/><BR/>why externally duplicate a network that is already in existence, or compromise the security of that network w/external affiliation w/known murderers?  sounds tactically and strategically stupid to me.<BR/>his first obligation would be to the lodge.  any external affiliation/linkage w/the likes of the klan would necessarily injure the lodge, and its world standing among other facets of world freemasonry. <BR/>***************************<BR/><BR/>&#39;As for Lincoln, you said he was the Fed bitch, I have refuted that he was. I never pretended to buy into his other myths, but his issuing the greenbacks and winning the war which those who backed the Fed did not want him to win suggests he was not the Feds bitch.&#39;<BR/><BR/>sorry, i don&#39;t buy your refutation, Myer&#39;s research as well as Dilorenzo&#39;s refutes your refutation.  the bankers didn&#39;t care who won...they&#39;d funded both sides, they made money on the war either way.....that&#39;s their game plan......always has been and always will be, what ever accomplishes their agenda, war being a prime impetus........ is that thought alien to you?  these cats claim no nationality, that&#39;s irrelevant to them.<BR/><BR/>early in his career, lincoln earned his money working for the robber barons/bankers (all agents of rothschild)... <BR/>his deciding to beat them w/ their own game, going rogue and cutting them out of the loop w/his own fiat greenbacks i&#39;m sure was cause for some tense moments until the bankers got the Natl. Bank Act passed, then they knew they had him, again, in hand by &#39;63.  i seriously doubt, they&#39;d let pass his insurrection, even as the situation was recovered.<BR/><BR/>&#39;His support for the National Banking Act seems at odds with this, and I suggested he may have been coerced or duped into supporting it.&#39;<BR/><BR/>he had no choice, By1863 Lincoln needed more money to win the war. Seeing to it that the president could not get the congressional authority to issue more greenbacks, the bankers proposed the National Bank Act. The Act passed and from this point on the entire US money supply would be created out of debt. Bankers would buy U.S. government bonds with money they created by issuing bank notes. This is essentially the same system we have today with the Federal Reserve. The U.S. Treasury issues Bonds, Notes, and Bills and the &#8220;Fed&#8221; buys them by simply printing money. These bonds, notes, and bills are now national debt and the taxpayers (you and I) get to pay the bankers unending interest on it. Remember that this debt was created by the bankers simply cranking the handle on their printing press, but the interest we pay them every year in taxes comes from our own hard work. &#8220;I have never yet had anyone who could, through logic and reason, justify the federal government borrowing the use of its own money.&#8221; - Wright Patman, Chair, House Committee on Banking and Currency.</p>
