<p>kikz-thanks for the long reply, and sorry for the delay.  I think we are not too far apart.<BR/><BR/>It might be helpful to go back 30 years for additional perspective.  South Carolina almost precipitated a civil war in 1832 when they nullified the tarriffs as an assertion of states rights, even though they had no constitutional right to do so.  <BR/><BR/>Jackson believed tarriffs were mainly a pretext that got the support of the people, by forces who wanted to promote disunion and a confederacy, which would have led to war with the North in the future.  <BR/><BR/>This conflict came in 1832-1833 after Jackson had vetoed the renewal of the 2nd banks charter, and conflict was averted by Jacksons patience, allowing the other southern states passions to ebb, and the compromise that agreed to lower tarriffs for the south over the next decade allowed SC to back down with some face.  Congressional approval for Jackson to use force and collect tarriffs at sea or diverting traffic to other ports played a role as well.  <BR/><BR/>Jackson making the Presidency as powerful as he did with his veto's and other actions led to even more distrust in the federal government, and the Presidents views became more of an issue, so Lincoln was perceived to be more of a threat than he otherwise might have been if not for Jackson, and the experience of the failure in 1833 by those forces who wanted secession proved beneficial.<BR/><BR/>Lincoln was protecting the North, seeing as he was at war with the South for most of his Presidency, but he inherited the problems and his position on slavery, even if not an abolitionist, but openly supporting a future  congressional ban on slavery in the territories, added slavery to the tarriff issues,  which served as the pretext for getting the people behind secession. These these issues however were simmering long before Lincoln.<BR/><BR/>That said, perhaps if Lincoln handled the crisis as did Jackson, a compromise could have been reached and war averted, but it seems war would have been inevitable even if Lincoln did not go to war.  <BR/><BR/>The Rothschilds strategy is fund 2 sides, and trigger a war, collecting profits from both sides.  This one killed 600,000 which is the equivelant of 5 million today, but if not fought then, we likely would have had perpetual war or repeated wars that killed many more.  That said, I am not sure Lincoln did all he could to have averted a war and preserved the union by some other means.<BR/><BR/>Lincolns actions on the income tax, suspending habeus corpus and the constitution, etc were made possible only by the war.  Those who seek to exert control of government prefer a hamiltonian/jacksonian type of government with a strong central government and executive branch.  Thats exactly what the conflicts of 1833 and the Civil War gave us, perhaps by design.  In the end, they got most of what they wanted.<BR/><BR/>As for who the international bankers wanted to win, I think they preferred nobody win, since then they could have a war every 20 years in the US. Once the North won, then they descended on the South like vultures. Perhaps they saw Lincoln as an obstacle to being able to do that, and it was this and not the greenbacks that were the cause for him being shot.<BR/><BR/>As for the National Banking Act, lack of funding, or no more greenbacks, was a form of coercion. In 1862, Lincoln gave a speech to Congress proposing the government deposit bonds at the Treasury and issue it's own money and earn interest, and what resulted was an absolute corruption of what he had proposed. <BR/><BR/>Patman was the last voice of reason on this issue.  Ron Pauls call for a gold standard is why he is not shut up and is allowed to speak against the Fed. <BR/><BR/>We had no choice but to go through the Rothschilds for the railroads, we had to import the steel for the tracks in the early years. We were a nation rich in resources, land and labour, but they controlled the financing through their agents in Wall Street, and they ended up assuming defacto control of the railroads with the depressions of 1873 and 1893.<BR/><BR/>As for Pike, his associating with the KKK seems not wise, and is perhaps the best reason for the argument that he was not. Perhaps anti-Masonry sentiment was an objective behind naming Pike, perhaps to weaken it or strengthen it even.  <BR/><BR/>The Klan served the purpose of those behind the secession after the war to keep the country polarized, and those across the Atlantic acting through agents in the US were behind it. Pike may be innocent, but only those at the highest levels know for sure, and they don't talk about some things.  Secrets of course fuel conspiracy theories. The banksters seem to have a hand in every institution, public, private and secret, which does not make them evil, and 99% of those within are unaware of what goes on at the top, so who knows. <BR/>     <BR/>But as Les says, I am probably saying a lot here without saying much.</p>
