<dd class='comment-body'>
<p>pot said..<BR/>&#39;South Carolina almost precipitated a civil war in 1832 when they nullified the tarriffs as an assertion of states rights, even though they had no constitutional right to do so.&#39;<BR/><BR/>though the several southern states upon voluntary entry into the union of states had ceded state control of regulating import tariffs to the fed gov (stupid, in my opine) it was upon condition and expectation of reciprocity.  reciprocity that their interests would be seen to fairly and impartially for their contributions.  however even during jackson&#39;s day, this was not to be, &#39;29 &amp; &#39;32 respectively broke the camel&#39;s back, hence SC&#39;s nullification, and threat of secession - which did bring some measure of relief as the rate on imports held at least until the end of Jackson&#39;s term in &#39;37.  we know what happened after that until &#39;61, where the tariff reached beyond 45%.   <BR/><BR/>all those years til &#39;61 they and the other newly admitted southern states paid their fair share to the common good of the country which had pledged to look after them, and didn&#39;t.  if you had been in their shoes... what would you have done as the tariff on imports steadily rose and your state got no compensation from the surplus, but saw your northern neighbors&#39; infrastructure not only maintained but enhanced at your expense, and you were threatened by force of invasion to keep paying?   <BR/><BR/>one would think, w/in that time period the south or its more enlightened sons would&#39;ve seen the writing on the wall, and made better preparations for what they had to fathom some day would come...<BR/><BR/><BR/>for more info on the railroad&#39;s man lincoln:<BR/>http://www.lewrockwell.com/dilorenzo/dilorenzo53.html<BR/><BR/><BR/>&#39;As for Pike, his associating with the KKK seems not wise, and is perhaps the best reason for the argument that he was not. Perhaps anti-Masonry sentiment was an objective behind naming Pike, perhaps to weaken it or strengthen it even.&#39;<BR/>&#39;The Klan served the purpose of those behind the secession after the war to keep the country polarized...&#39;<BR/><BR/><BR/>what i&#39;ve read of Pike... he didn&#39;t have a problem w/the color of a person&#39;s skin (race).<BR/>from his writings i gather if he did express disdain for a person/institution it was either on the grounds of willful ignorance or tyranny inflicted on others.  <BR/><BR/>as far as any entity keeping the country polarized; reconstruction by the union, carpetbaggers/scalawags did quite the ample job of that.</p>
</dd>
